27 |## Searching Documentation
28 |
29 |```sh
30 |mix usage_rules.search_docs "search term" -p bolty -p ash -p ash_state_machine
31 |```
32 |
33 |## Available Mix Tasks
34 |
35 |- `mix ash` - Prints Ash help information
36 |- `mix ash.codegen` - Runs all codegen tasks for any extension on any resource/domain in your application.
37 |- `mix ash.extend` - Adds an extension or extensions to the given domain/resource
38 |- `mix ash.gen.base_resource` - Generates a base resource. This is a module that you can use instead of `Ash.Resource`, for consistency.
39 |- `mix ash.gen.change` - Generates a custom change module.
40 |- `mix ash.gen.custom_expression` - Generates a custom expression module.
41 |- `mix ash.gen.domain` - Generates an Ash.Domain
42 |- `mix ash.gen.enum` - Generates an Ash.Type.Enum
43 |- `mix ash.gen.gettext` - Copies Ash's .pot file for error message translation
44 |- `mix ash.gen.preparation` - Generates a custom preparation module.
45 |- `mix ash.gen.resource` - Generate and configure an Ash.Resource.
46 |- `mix ash.gen.validation` - Generates a custom validation module.
47 |- `mix ash.generate_livebook` - Generates a Livebook for each Ash domain
48 |- `mix ash.generate_policy_charts` - Generates a Mermaid Flow Chart for a given resource's policies.
49 |- `mix ash.generate_resource_diagrams` - Generates Mermaid Resource Diagrams for each Ash domain
50 |- `mix ash.gettext.extract` - Extracts Ash error messages into a .pot file
51 |- `mix ash.install` - Installs Ash into a project. Should be called with `mix igniter.install ash`
52 |- `mix ash.manifest.dump` - Dump the Ash app manifest as JSON
53 |- `mix ash.migrate` - Runs all migration tasks for any extension on any resource/domain in your application.
54 |- `mix ash.patch.extend` - Adds an extension or extensions to the given domain/resource
55 |- `mix ash.reset` - Runs all tear down & setup tasks for any extension on any resource/domain in your application.
56 |- `mix ash.rollback` - Runs all rollback tasks for any extension on any resource/domain in your application.
57 |- `mix ash.setup` - Runs all setup tasks for any extension on any resource/domain in your application.
58 |- `mix ash.tear_down` - Runs all tear_down tasks for any extension on any resource/domain in your application.
59 |- `mix ash_state_machine.generate_flow_charts` - Generates Mermaid Flow Charts for each resource using `AshStateMachine`
60 |- `mix ash_state_machine.install` - Installs AshStateMachine
61 |- `mix ash_state_machine.install.docs`
62 |<!-- usage-rules-skill-end -->


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/actions.md

1   |# Actions
2   |
3   |- Create specific, well-named actions rather than generic ones
4   |- Put all business logic inside action definitions
5   |- Use hooks like `Ash.Changeset.after_action/2`, `Ash.Changeset.before_action/2` to add additional logic
6   |  inside the same transaction.
7   |- Use hooks like `Ash.Changeset.after_transaction/2`, `Ash.Changeset.before_transaction/2` to add additional logic
8   |  outside the transaction.
9   |- Use action arguments for inputs that need validation
10  |- Use preparations to modify queries before execution
11  |- Preparations support `where` clauses for conditional execution
12  |- Use `only_when_valid?` to skip preparations when the query is invalid
13  |- Use changes to modify changesets before execution
14  |- Use validations to validate changesets before execution
15  |- Prefer domain code interfaces to call actions instead of directly building queries/changesets and calling functions in the `Ash` module
16  |- A resource could be *only generic actions*. This can be useful when you are using a resource only to model behavior.
17  |- Instead of defining functions in the domain, you should be defining actions and exposing them through code interface calls in the domain. Use standard actions when they fit what you're doing and generic actions when you need arbitrary functionality.
18  |
19  |## Error Handling
20  |
21  |Functions to call actions, like `Ash.create` and code interfaces like `MyApp.Accounts.register_user` all return ok/error tuples. All have `!` variations, like `Ash.create!` and `MyApp.Accounts.register_user!`. Use the `!` variations when you want to "let it crash", like if looking something up that should definitely exist, or calling an action that should always succeed. Always prefer the raising `!` variation over something like `{:ok, user} = MyApp.Accounts.register_user(...)`.
22  |
23  |All Ash code returns errors in the form of `{:error, error_class}`. Ash categorizes errors into four main classes:
24  |
25  |1. **Forbidden** (`Ash.Error.Forbidden`) - Occurs when a user attempts an action they don't have permission to perform
26  |2. **Invalid** (`Ash.Error.Invalid`) - Occurs when input data doesn't meet validation requirements
27  |3. **Framework** (`Ash.Error.Framework`) - Occurs when there's an issue with how Ash is being used
28  |4. **Unknown** (`Ash.Error.Unknown`) - Occurs for unexpected errors that don't fit the other categories
29  |
30  |These error classes help you catch and handle errors at an appropriate level of granularity. An error class will always be the "worst" (highest in the above list) error class from above. Each error class can contain multiple underlying errors, accessible via the `errors` field on the exception.
31  |
32  |## Using Validations
33  |
34  |Validations ensure that data meets your business requirements before it gets processed by an action. Unlike changes, validations cannot modify the changeset - they can only validate it or add errors.
35  |
36  |Validations work on both changesets and queries. Built-in validations that support queries include:
37  |- `action_is`, `argument_does_not_equal`, `argument_equals`, `argument_in`
38  |- `compare`, `confirm`, `match`, `negate`, `one_of`, `present`, `string_length`
39  |- Custom validations that implement the `supports/1` callback
40  |
41  |Common validation patterns:
42  |
43  |```elixir
44  |# Built-in validations with custom messages
45  |validate compare(:age, greater_than_or_equal_to: 18) do
46  |  message "You must be at least 18 years old"
47  |end
48  |validate match(:email, "@")
49  |validate one_of(:status, [:active, :inactive, :pending])
50  |
51  |# Conditional validations with where clauses
52  |validate present(:phone_number) do
53  |  where present(:contact_method) and eq(:contact_method, "phone")
54  |end
55  |
56  |# only_when_valid? - skip validation if prior validations failed
57  |validate expensive_validation() do
58  |  only_when_valid? true
59  |end
60  |
61  |# Action-specific vs global validations
62  |actions do
63  |  create :sign_up do
64  |    validate present([:email, :password])  # Only for this action
65  |  end
66  |  
67  |  read :search do
68  |    argument :email, :string
69  |    validate match(:email, ~r/^[^\s]+@[^\s]+\.[^\s]+$/)  # Validates query arguments
70  |  end
71  |end
72  |
73  |validations do
74  |  validate present([:title, :body]), on: [:create, :update]  # Multiple actions
75  |end
76  |```
77  |
78  |- Create **custom validation modules** for complex validation logic:
79  |  ```elixir
80  |  defmodule MyApp.Validations.UniqueUsername do
81  |    use Ash.Resource.Validation
82  |
83  |    @impl true
84  |    def init(opts), do: {:ok, opts}
85  |
86  |    @impl true
87  |    def validate(changeset, _opts, _context) do
88  |      # Validation logic here
89  |      # Return :ok or {:error, message}
90  |    end
91  |  end
92  |
93  |  # Usage in resource:
94  |  validate {MyApp.Validations.UniqueUsername, []}
95  |  ```
96  |
97  |- Make validations **atomic** when possible to ensure they work correctly with direct database operations by implementing the `atomic/3` callback in custom validation modules.
98  |
99  |  ```elixir
100 |  defmodule MyApp.Validations.IsEven do
101 |    # transform and validate opts
102 |
103 |    use Ash.Resource.Validation
104 |
105 |    @impl true
106 |    def init(opts) do
107 |      if is_atom(opts[:attribute]) do
108 |        {:ok, opts}
109 |      else
110 |        {:error, "attribute must be an atom!"}
111 |      end
112 |    end
113 |
114 |    @impl true
115 |    # This is optional, but useful to have in addition to validation
116 |    # so you get early feedback for validations that can otherwise
117 |    # only run in the datalayer
118 |    def validate(changeset, opts, _context) do
119 |      value = Ash.Changeset.get_attribute(changeset, opts[:attribute])
120 |
121 |      if is_nil(value) || (is_number(value) && rem(value, 2) == 0) do
122 |        :ok
123 |      else
124 |        {:error, field: opts[:attribute], message: "must be an even number"}
125 |      end
126 |    end
127 |
128 |    @impl true
129 |    def atomic(changeset, opts, context) do
130 |      {:atomic,
131 |        # the list of attributes that are involved in the validation
132 |        [opts[:attribute]],
133 |        # the condition that should cause the error
134 |        # here we refer to the new value or the current value
135 |        expr(rem(^atomic_ref(opts[:attribute]), 2) != 0),
136 |        # the error expression
137 |        expr(
138 |          error(^InvalidAttribute, %{
139 |            field: ^opts[:attribute],
140 |            # the value that caused the error
141 |            value: ^atomic_ref(opts[:attribute]),
142 |            # the message to display
143 |            message: ^(context.message || "%{field} must be an even number"),
144 |            vars: %{field: ^opts[:attribute]}
145 |          })
146 |        )
147 |      }
148 |    end
149 |  end
150 |  ```
151 |
152 |- **Avoid redundant validations** - Don't add validations that duplicate attribute constraints:
153 |  ```elixir
154 |  # WRONG - redundant validation
155 |  attribute :name, :string do
156 |    allow_nil? false
157 |    constraints min_length: 1
158 |  end
159 |
160 |  validate present(:name) do  # Redundant! allow_nil? false already handles this
161 |    message "Name is required"
162 |  end
163 |
164 |  validate attribute_does_not_equal(:name, "") do  # Redundant! min_length: 1 already handles this
165 |    message "Name cannot be empty"
166 |  end
167 |
168 |  # CORRECT - let attribute constraints handle basic validation
169 |  attribute :name, :string do
170 |    allow_nil? false
171 |    constraints min_length: 1
172 |  end
173 |  ```
174 |
175 |## Using Preparations
176 |
177 |Preparations modify queries before they're executed. They are used to add filters, sorts, or other query modifications based on the query context.
178 |
179 |Common preparation patterns:
180 |
181 |```elixir
182 |# Built-in preparations
183 |prepare build(sort: [created_at: :desc])
184 |prepare build(filter: [active: true])
185 |
186 |# Conditional preparations with where clauses
187 |prepare build(filter: [visible: true]) do
188 |  where argument_equals(:include_hidden, false)
189 |end
190 |
191 |# only_when_valid? - skip preparation if prior validations failed
192 |prepare expensive_preparation() do
193 |  only_when_valid? true
194 |end
195 |
196 |# Action-specific vs global preparations
197 |actions do
198 |  read :recent do
199 |    prepare build(sort: [created_at: :desc], limit: 10)
200 |  end
201 |end
202 |
203 |preparations do
204 |  prepare build(filter: [deleted: false]), on: [:read, :update]
205 |end
206 |```
207 |
208 |## Using Changes
209 |
210 |Changes allow you to modify the changeset before it gets processed by an action. Unlike validations, changes can manipulate attribute values, add attributes, or perform other data transformations.
211 |
212 |Common change patterns:
213 |
214 |```elixir
215 |# Built-in changes with conditions
216 |change set_attribute(:status, "pending")
217 |change relate_actor(:creator) do
218 |  where present(:actor)
219 |end
220 |change atomic_update(:counter, expr(^counter + 1))
221 |
222 |# Action-specific vs global changes
223 |actions do
224 |  create :sign_up do
225 |    change set_attribute(:joined_at, expr(now()))  # Only for this action
226 |  end
227 |end
228 |
229 |changes do
230 |  change set_attribute(:updated_at, expr(now())), on: :update  # Multiple actions
231 |  change manage_relationship(:items, type: :append), on: [:create, :update]
232 |end
233 |```
234 |
235 |- Create **custom change modules** for reusable transformation logic:
236 |  ```elixir
237 |  defmodule MyApp.Changes.SlugifyTitle do
238 |    use Ash.Resource.Change
239 |
240 |    def change(changeset, _opts, _context) do
241 |      title = Ash.Changeset.get_attribute(changeset, :title)
242 |
243 |      if title do
244 |        slug = title |> String.downcase() |> String.replace(~r/[^a-z0-9]+/, "-")
245 |        Ash.Changeset.change_attribute(changeset, :slug, slug)
246 |      else
247 |        changeset
248 |      end
249 |    end
250 |  end
251 |
252 |  # Usage in resource:
253 |  change {MyApp.Changes.SlugifyTitle, []}
254 |  ```
255 |
256 |- Create a **change module with lifecycle hooks** to handle complex multi-step operations:
257 |
258 |  ```elixir
259 |  defmodule MyApp.Changes.ProcessOrder do
260 |    use Ash.Resource.Change
261 |
262 |    def change(changeset, _opts, context) do
263 |      changeset
264 |      |> Ash.Changeset.before_transaction(fn changeset ->
265 |        # Runs before the transaction starts
266 |        # Use for external API calls, logging, etc.
267 |        MyApp.ExternalService.reserve_inventory(changeset, scope: context)
268 |        changeset
269 |      end)
270 |      |> Ash.Changeset.before_action(fn changeset ->
271 |        # Runs inside the transaction before the main action
272 |        # Use for related database changes in the same transaction
273 |        Ash.Changeset.change_attribute(changeset, :processed_at, DateTime.utc_now())
274 |      end)
275 |      |> Ash.Changeset.after_action(fn changeset, result ->
276 |        # Runs inside the transaction after the main action, only on success
277 |        # Use for related database changes that depend on the result
278 |        MyApp.Inventory.update_stock_levels(result, scope: context)
279 |        {changeset, result}
280 |      end)
281 |      |> Ash.Changeset.after_transaction(fn changeset,
282 |        {:ok, result} ->
283 |          # Runs after the transaction completes (success or failure)
284 |          # Use for notifications, external systems, etc.
285 |          MyApp.Mailer.send_order_confirmation(result, scope: context)
286 |          {changeset, result}
287 |
288 |        {:error, error} ->
289 |          # Runs after the transaction completes (success or failure)
290 |          # Use for notifications, external systems, etc.
291 |          MyApp.Mailer.send_order_issue_notice(result, scope: context)
292 |          {:error, error}
293 |      end)
294 |    end
295 |  end
296 |
297 |  # Usage in resource:
298 |  change {MyApp.Changes.ProcessOrder, []}
299 |  ```
300 |
301 |## Atomic Changes
302 |
303 |Atomic changes execute directly in the database as part of the update query, without requiring the record to be loaded first. This provides better performance and correct behavior under concurrent updates.
304 |
305 |**Why atomic matters:**
306 |- Avoids race conditions (e.g., incrementing a counter)
307 |- Better performance (no round-trip to load the record)
308 |- Required for bulk operations to work efficiently
309 |
310 |**Built-in atomic changes:**
311 |```elixir
312 |# Increment a counter atomically
313 |change atomic_update(:view_count, expr(view_count + 1))
314 |
315 |# Set a value using an expression
316 |change set_attribute(:updated_at, expr(now()))
317 |```
318 |
319 |**Making custom changes atomic:**
320 |Implement the `atomic/3` callback to support atomic execution:
321 |
322 |```elixir
323 |defmodule MyApp.Changes.IncrementVersion do
324 |  use Ash.Resource.Change
325 |
326 |  @impl true
327 |  def change(changeset, _opts, _context) do
328 |    # Fallback for non-atomic execution
329 |    current = Ash.Changeset.get_attribute(changeset, :version) || 0
330 |    Ash.Changeset.change_attribute(changeset, :version, current + 1)
331 |  end
332 |
333 |  @impl true
334 |  def atomic(_changeset, _opts, _context) do
335 |    # Atomic implementation - runs in the database
336 |    {:atomic, %{version: expr(coalesce(version, 0) + 1)}}
337 |  end
338 |end
339 |```
340 |
341 |## Using `require_atomic? false`
342 |
343 |By default, update and destroy actions require all changes and validations to support atomic execution. If they don't, the action will raise an error.
344 |
345 |**IMPORTANT:** When you see `require_atomic? false` on an action, carefully consider whether it is truly necessary. This option should be used sparingly.
346 |
347 |**When `require_atomic? false` is needed:**
348 |- The action has `before_action` or `around_action` hooks that need to read or modify the record
349 |- A change reads the current record state (e.g., `Ash.Changeset.get_data/2`) and cannot be rewritten atomically
350 |- Complex validations that cannot be expressed as database expressions
351 |
352 |**When `require_atomic? false` is NOT needed:**
353 |- Simple attribute transformations (these can usually be made atomic)
354 |- Setting timestamps or default values (use `expr(now())` instead)
355 |- Incrementing counters (use `atomic_update/2`)
356 |- After-action hooks (these don't prevent atomic execution)
357 |- After-transaction hooks (these don't prevent atomic execution)
358 |
359 |```elixir
360 |actions do
361 |  update :update do
362 |    # AVOID unless truly necessary
363 |    require_atomic? false
364 |  end
365 |
366 |  update :increment_views do
367 |    # GOOD - fully atomic, no need to disable
368 |    change atomic_update(:view_count, expr(view_count + 1))
369 |  end
370 |end
371 |```
372 |
373 |If you find yourself adding `require_atomic? false`, first check if your changes and validations can be rewritten with `atomic/3` callbacks. Only disable atomic requirements when the action genuinely needs to read or manipulate the record in hooks.
374 |
375 |## Custom Modules vs. Anonymous Functions
376 |
377 |Prefer to put code in its own module and refer to that in changes, preparations, validations etc.
378 |
379 |For example, prefer this:
380 |
381 |```elixir
382 |defmodule MyApp.MyDomain.MyResource.Changes.SlugifyName do
383 |  use Ash.Resource.Change
384 |
385 |  def change(changeset, _, _) do
386 |    Ash.Changeset.before_action(changeset, fn changeset, _ ->
387 |      slug = MyApp.Slug.get()
388 |      Ash.Changeset.force_change_attribute(changeset, :slug, slug)
389 |    end)
390 |  end
391 |end
392 |
393 |change MyApp.MyDomain.MyResource.Changes.SlugifyName
394 |```
395 |
396 |## Action Types
397 |
398 |- **Read**: For retrieving records
399 |- **Create**: For creating records
400 |- **Update**: For changing records
401 |- **Destroy**: For removing records
402 |- **Generic**: For custom operations that don't fit the other types
403 |
404 |
405 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/aggregates.md

1   |# Aggregates
2   |
3   |Aggregates allow you to retrieve summary information over groups of related data, like counts, sums, or averages. Define aggregates in the `aggregates` block of a resource.
4   |
5   |Aggregates can work over relationships or directly over unrelated resources:
6   |
7   |```elixir
8   |aggregates do
9   |  # Related aggregates - use relationship path
10  |  count :published_post_count, :posts do
11  |    filter expr(published == true)
12  |  end
13  |
14  |  sum :total_sales, :orders, :amount
15  |
16  |  exists :is_admin, :roles do
17  |    filter expr(name == "admin")
18  |  end
19  |
20  |  # Unrelated aggregates - use resource module directly
21  |  count :matching_profiles_count, Profile do
22  |    filter expr(name == parent(name))
23  |  end
24  |  
25  |  sum :total_report_score, Report, :score do
26  |    filter expr(author_name == parent(name))
27  |  end
28  |  
29  |  exists :has_reports, Report do
30  |    filter expr(author_name == parent(name))
31  |  end
32  |end
33  |```
34  |
35  |For unrelated aggregates, use `parent/1` to reference fields from the source resource.
36  |
37  |## Aggregate Types
38  |
39  |- **count**: Counts related items meeting criteria
40  |- **sum**: Sums a field across related items
41  |- **exists**: Returns boolean indicating if matching related items exist (also supports unrelated resources)
42  |- **first**: Gets the first related value matching criteria
43  |- **list**: Lists the related values for a specific field
44  |- **max**: Gets the maximum value of a field
45  |- **min**: Gets the minimum value of a field
46  |- **avg**: Gets the average value of a field
47  |
48  |## Using Aggregates
49  |
50  |```elixir
51  |# Using code interface options (preferred)
52  |users = MyDomain.list_users!(
53  |  load: [:published_post_count, :total_sales],
54  |  query: [
55  |    filter: [published_post_count: [greater_than: 5]],
56  |    sort: [published_post_count: :desc]
57  |  ]
58  |)
59  |
60  |# Manual query building (for complex cases)
61  |User |> Ash.Query.filter(published_post_count > 5) |> Ash.read!()
62  |
63  |# Loading on existing records
64  |Ash.load!(users, :published_post_count)
65  |```
66  |
67  |### Join Filters
68  |
69  |For complex aggregates involving multiple relationships, use join filters:
70  |
71  |```elixir
72  |aggregates do
73  |  sum :redeemed_deal_amount, [:redeems, :deal], :amount do
74  |    # Filter on the aggregate as a whole
75  |    filter expr(redeems.redeemed == true)
76  |
77  |    # Apply filters to specific relationship steps
78  |    join_filter :redeems, expr(redeemed == true)
79  |    join_filter [:redeems, :deal], expr(active == parent(require_active))
80  |  end
81  |end
82  |```
83  |
84  |## Inline Aggregates
85  |
86  |Use aggregates inline within expressions:
87  |
88  |```elixir
89  |# Related inline aggregates
90  |calculate :grade_percentage, :decimal, expr(
91  |  count(answers, query: [filter: expr(correct == true)]) * 100 /
92  |  count(answers)
93  |)
94  |
95  |# Unrelated inline aggregates
96  |calculate :profile_count, :integer, expr(
97  |  count(Profile, filter: expr(name == parent(name)))
98  |)
99  |
100 |calculate :stats, :map, expr(%{
101 |  profiles: count(Profile, filter: expr(active == true)),
102 |  reports: count(Report, filter: expr(author_name == parent(name))),
103 |  has_active_profile: exists(Profile, active == true and name == parent(name))
104 |})
105 |```
106 |
107 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/ash.md

1 |# Rules for working with Ash
2 |
3 |## Understanding Ash
4 |
5 |Ash is an opinionated, composable framework for building applications in Elixir. It provides a declarative approach to modeling your domain with resources at the center. Read documentation  *before* attempting to use its features. Do not assume that you have prior knowledge of the framework or its conventions.
6 |
7 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/authorization.md

1   |# Authorization
2   |
3   |- When performing administrative actions, you can bypass authorization with `authorize?: false`
4   |- To run actions as a particular user, look that user up and pass it as the `actor` option
5   |- Always set the actor on the query/changeset/input, not when calling the action
6   |- Use policies to define authorization rules
7   |
8   |```elixir
9   |# Good
10  |Post
11  ||> Ash.Query.for_read(:read, %{}, actor: current_user)
12  ||> Ash.read!()
13  |
14  |# BAD, DO NOT DO THIS
15  |Post
16  ||> Ash.Query.for_read(:read, %{})
17  ||> Ash.read!(actor: current_user)
18  |```
19  |
20  |## Policies
21  |
22  |To use policies, add the `Ash.Policy.Authorizer` to your resource:
23  |
24  |```elixir
25  |defmodule MyApp.Post do
26  |  use Ash.Resource,
27  |    domain: MyApp.Blog,
28  |    authorizers: [Ash.Policy.Authorizer]
29  |
30  |  # Rest of resource definition...
31  |end
32  |```
33  |
34  |## Policy Basics
35  |
36  |Policies determine what actions on a resource are permitted for a given actor. Define policies in the `policies` block:
37  |
38  |```elixir
39  |policies do
40  |  # A simple policy that applies to all read actions
41  |  policy action_type(:read) do
42  |    # Authorize if record is public
43  |    authorize_if expr(public == true)
44  |
45  |    # Authorize if actor is the owner
46  |    authorize_if relates_to_actor_via(:owner)
47  |  end
48  |
49  |  # A policy for create actions
50  |  policy action_type(:create) do
51  |    # Only allow active users to create records
52  |    forbid_unless actor_attribute_equals(:active, true)
53  |
54  |    # Ensure the record being created relates to the actor
55  |    authorize_if relating_to_actor(:owner)
56  |  end
57  |end
58  |```
59  |
60  |## Policy Evaluation Flow
61  |
62  |Policies evaluate from top to bottom with the following logic:
63  |
64  |1. All policies that apply to an action must pass for the action to be allowed
65  |2. Within each policy, checks evaluate from top to bottom
66  |3. The first check that produces a decision determines the policy result
67  |4. If no check produces a decision, the policy defaults to forbidden
68  |
69  |## IMPORTANT: Policy Check Logic
70  |
71  |**the first check that yields a result determines the policy outcome**
72  |
73  |```elixir
74  |# WRONG - This is OR logic, not AND logic!
75  |policy action_type(:update) do
76  |  authorize_if actor_attribute_equals(:admin?, true)    # If this passes, policy passes
77  |  authorize_if relates_to_actor_via(:owner)           # Only checked if first fails
78  |end
79  |```
80  |
81  |To require BOTH conditions in that example, you would use `forbid_unless` for the first condition:
82  |
83  |```elixir
84  |# CORRECT - This requires BOTH conditions
85  |policy action_type(:update) do
86  |  forbid_unless actor_attribute_equals(:admin?, true)  # Must be admin
87  |  authorize_if relates_to_actor_via(:owner)           # AND must be owner
88  |end
89  |```
90  |
91  |Alternative patterns for AND logic:
92  |- Use multiple separate policies (each must pass independently)
93  |- Use a single complex expression with `expr(condition1 and condition2)`
94  |- Use `forbid_unless` for required conditions, then `authorize_if` for the final check
95  |
96  |## Bypass Policies
97  |
98  |Use bypass policies to allow certain actors to bypass other policy restrictions. This should be used almost exclusively for admin bypasses.
99  |
100 |```elixir
101 |policies do
102 |  # Bypass policy for admins - if this passes, other policies don't need to pass
103 |  bypass actor_attribute_equals(:admin, true) do
104 |    authorize_if always()
105 |  end
106 |
107 |  # Regular policies follow...
108 |  policy action_type(:read) do
109 |    # ...
110 |  end
111 |end
112 |```
113 |
114 |## Field Policies
115 |
116 |Field policies control access to specific fields (attributes, calculations, aggregates):
117 |
118 |```elixir
119 |field_policies do
120 |  # Only supervisors can see the salary field
121 |  field_policy :salary do
122 |    authorize_if actor_attribute_equals(:role, :supervisor)
123 |  end
124 |
125 |  # Allow access to all other fields
126 |  field_policy :* do
127 |    authorize_if always()
128 |  end
129 |end
130 |```
131 |
132 |## Policy Checks
133 |
134 |There are two main types of checks used in policies:
135 |
136 |1. **Simple checks** - Return true/false answers (e.g., "is the actor an admin?")
137 |2. **Filter checks** - Return filters to apply to data (e.g., "only show records owned by the actor")
138 |
139 |You can use built-in checks or create custom ones:
140 |
141 |```elixir
142 |# Built-in checks
143 |authorize_if actor_attribute_equals(:role, :admin)
144 |authorize_if relates_to_actor_via(:owner)
145 |authorize_if expr(public == true)
146 |
147 |# Custom check module
148 |authorize_if MyApp.Checks.ActorHasPermission
149 |```
150 |
151 |### Custom Policy Checks
152 |
153 |Create custom checks by implementing `Ash.Policy.SimpleCheck` or `Ash.Policy.FilterCheck`:
154 |
155 |```elixir
156 |# Simple check - returns true/false
157 |defmodule MyApp.Checks.ActorHasRole do
158 |  use Ash.Policy.SimpleCheck
159 |
160 |  def match?(%{role: actor_role}, _context, opts) do
161 |    actor_role == (opts[:role] || :admin)
162 |  end
163 |  def match?(_, _, _), do: false
164 |end
165 |
166 |# Filter check - returns query filter
167 |defmodule MyApp.Checks.VisibleToUserLevel do
168 |  use Ash.Policy.FilterCheck
169 |
170 |  def filter(actor, _authorizer, _opts) do
171 |    expr(visibility_level <= ^actor.user_level)
172 |  end
173 |end
174 |
175 |# Usage
176 |policy action_type(:read) do
177 |  authorize_if {MyApp.Checks.ActorHasRole, role: :manager}
178 |  authorize_if MyApp.Checks.VisibleToUserLevel
179 |end
180 |```
181 |
182 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/calculations.md

1   |# Calculations
2   |
3   |Calculations allow you to define derived values based on a resource's attributes or related data. Define calculations in the `calculations` block of a resource:
4   |
5   |```elixir
6   |calculations do
7   |  # Simple expression calculation
8   |  calculate :full_name, :string, expr(first_name <> " " <> last_name)
9   |
10  |  # Expression with conditions
11  |  calculate :status_label, :string, expr(
12  |    cond do
13  |      status == :active -> "Active"
14  |      status == :pending -> "Pending Review"
15  |      true -> "Inactive"
16  |    end
17  |  )
18  |
19  |  # Using module calculations for more complex logic
20  |  calculate :risk_score, :integer, {MyApp.Calculations.RiskScore, min: 0, max: 100}
21  |end
22  |```
23  |
24  |## Expression Calculations
25  |
26  |Expression calculations use Ash expressions and can be pushed down to the data layer when possible:
27  |
28  |```elixir
29  |calculations do
30  |  # Simple string concatenation
31  |  calculate :full_name, :string, expr(first_name <> " " <> last_name)
32  |
33  |  # Math operations
34  |  calculate :total_with_tax, :decimal, expr(amount * (1 + tax_rate))
35  |
36  |  # Date manipulation
37  |  calculate :days_since_created, :integer, expr(
38  |    date_diff(^now(), inserted_at, :day)
39  |  )
40  |end
41  |```
42  |
43  |## Expressions
44  |
45  |In order to use expressions outside of resources, changes, preparations etc. you will need to use `Ash.Expr`.
46  |
47  |It provides both `expr/1` and template helpers like `actor/1` and `arg/1`.
48  |
49  |For example:
50  |
51  |```elixir
52  |import Ash.Expr
53  |
54  |Author
55  ||> Ash.Query.aggregate(:count_of_my_favorited_posts, :count, [:posts], query: [
56  |  filter: expr(favorited_by(user_id: ^actor(:id)))
57  |])
58  |```
59  |
60  |See the expressions guide for more information on what is available in expresisons and
61  |how to use them.
62  |
63  |## Module Calculations
64  |
65  |For complex calculations, create a module that implements `Ash.Resource.Calculation`:
66  |
67  |```elixir
68  |defmodule MyApp.Calculations.FullName do
69  |  use Ash.Resource.Calculation
70  |
71  |  # Validate and transform options
72  |  @impl true
73  |  def init(opts) do
74  |    {:ok, Map.put_new(opts, :separator, " ")}
75  |  end
76  |
77  |  # Specify what data needs to be loaded
78  |  @impl true
79  |  def load(_query, _opts, _context) do
80  |    [:first_name, :last_name]
81  |  end
82  |
83  |  # Implement the calculation logic
84  |  @impl true
85  |  def calculate(records, opts, _context) do
86  |    Enum.map(records, fn record ->
87  |      [record.first_name, record.last_name]
88  |      |> Enum.reject(&is_nil/1)
89  |      |> Enum.join(opts.separator)
90  |    end)
91  |  end
92  |end
93  |
94  |# Usage in a resource
95  |calculations do
96  |  calculate :full_name, :string, {MyApp.Calculations.FullName, separator: ", "}
97  |end
98  |```
99  |
100 |## Calculations with Arguments
101 |
102 |You can define calculations that accept arguments:
103 |
104 |```elixir
105 |calculations do
106 |  calculate :full_name, :string, expr(first_name <> ^arg(:separator) <> last_name) do
107 |    argument :separator, :string do
108 |      allow_nil? false
109 |      default " "
110 |      constraints [allow_empty?: true, trim?: false]
111 |    end
112 |  end
113 |end
114 |```
115 |
116 |## Using Calculations
117 |
118 |```elixir
119 |# Using code interface options (preferred)
120 |users = MyDomain.list_users!(load: [full_name: [separator: ", "]])
121 |
122 |# Filtering and sorting
123 |users = MyDomain.list_users!(
124 |  query: [
125 |    filter: [full_name: [separator: " ", value: "John Doe"]],
126 |    sort: [full_name: {[separator: " "], :asc}]
127 |  ]
128 |)
129 |
130 |# Manual query building (for complex cases)
131 |User |> Ash.Query.load(full_name: [separator: ", "]) |> Ash.read!()
132 |
133 |# Loading on existing records
134 |Ash.load!(users, :full_name)
135 |```
136 |
137 |### Code Interface for Calculations
138 |
139 |Define calculation functions on your domain for standalone use:
140 |
141 |```elixir
142 |# In your domain
143 |resource User do
144 |  define_calculation :full_name, args: [:first_name, :last_name, {:optional, :separator}]
145 |end
146 |
147 |# Then call it directly
148 |MyDomain.full_name("John", "Doe", ", ")  # Returns "John, Doe"
149 |```
150 |
151 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/code_interfaces.md

1   |# Code Interfaces
2   |
3   |Domains and Resources can define code interfaces. Prefer writing code interfaces instead of regular elixir functions.
4   |
5   |Use code interfaces on domains to define the contract for calling into Ash resources. See the [Code interface guide for more](https://hexdocs.pm/ash/code-interfaces.html).
6   |
7   |Define code interfaces on the domain, like this:
8   |
9   |```elixir
10  |resource ResourceName do
11  |  define :fun_name, action: :action_name
12  |end
13  |```
14  |
15  |For more complex interfaces with custom transformations:
16  |
17  |```elixir
18  |define :custom_action do
19  |  action :action_name
20  |  args [:arg1, :arg2]
21  |
22  |  custom_input :arg1, MyType do
23  |    transform do
24  |      to :target_field
25  |      using &MyModule.transform_function/1
26  |    end
27  |  end
28  |end
29  |```
30  |
31  |Prefer using the primary read action for "get" style code interfaces, and using `get_by` when the field you are looking up by is the primary key or has an `identity` on the resource.
32  |
33  |```elixir
34  |resource ResourceName do
35  |  define :get_thing, action: :read, get_by: [:id]
36  |end
37  |```
38  |
39  |**Avoid direct Ash calls in web modules** - Don't use `Ash.get!/2` and `Ash.load!/2` directly in LiveViews/Controllers, similar to avoiding `Repo.get/2` outside context modules:
40  |
41  |You can also pass additional inputs in to code interfaces before the options:
42  |
43  |```elixir
44  |resource ResourceName do
45  |  define :create, action: :action_name, args: [:field1]
46  |end
47  |```
48  |
49  |```elixir
50  |Domain.create!(field1_value, %{field2: field2_value}, actor: current_user)
51  |```
52  |
53  |You should generally prefer using this map of extra inputs over defining optional arguments.
54  |
55  |```elixir
56  |# BAD - in LiveView/Controller
57  |group = MyApp.Resource |> Ash.get!(id) |> Ash.load!(rel: [:nested])
58  |
59  |# GOOD - use code interface with get_by
60  |resource DashboardGroup do
61  |  define :get_dashboard_group_by_id, action: :read, get_by: [:id]
62  |end
63  |
64  |# Then call:
65  |MyApp.Domain.get_dashboard_group_by_id!(id, load: [rel: [:nested]])
66  |```
67  |
68  |**Code interface options** - Prefer passing options directly to code interface functions rather than building queries manually:
69  |
70  |```elixir
71  |# PREFERRED - Use the query option for filter, sort, limit, etc.
72  |# the query option is passed to `Ash.Query.build/2`
73  |posts = MyApp.Blog.list_posts!(
74  |  query: [
75  |    filter: [status: :published],
76  |    sort: [published_at: :desc],
77  |    limit: 10
78  |  ],
79  |  load: [author: :profile, comments: [:author]]
80  |)
81  |
82  |# All query-related options go in the query parameter
83  |users = MyApp.Accounts.list_users!(
84  |  query: [filter: [active: true], sort: [created_at: :desc]],
85  |  load: [:profile]
86  |)
87  |
88  |# AVOID - Verbose manual query building
89  |query = MyApp.Post |> Ash.Query.filter(...) |> Ash.Query.load(...)
90  |posts = Ash.read!(query)
91  |```
92  |
93  |Supported options: `load:`, `query:` (which accepts `filter:`, `sort:`, `limit:`, `offset:`, etc.), `page:`, `stream?:`
94  |
95  |**Using Scopes in LiveViews** - When using `Ash.Scope`, the scope will typically be assigned to `scope` in LiveViews and used like so:
96  |
97  |```elixir
98  |# In your LiveView
99  |MyApp.Blog.create_post!("new post", scope: socket.assigns.scope)
100 |```
101 |
102 |Inside action hooks and callbacks, use the provided `context` parameter as your scope instead:
103 |
104 |```elixir
105 ||> Ash.Changeset.before_transaction(fn changeset, context ->
106 |  MyApp.ExternalService.reserve_inventory(changeset, scope: context)
107 |  changeset
108 |end)
109 |```
110 |
111 |## Authorization Functions
112 |
113 |For each action defined in a code interface, Ash automatically generates corresponding authorization check functions:
114 |
115 |- `can_action_name?(actor, params \\ %{}, opts \\ [])` - Returns `true`/`false` for authorization checks
116 |- `can_action_name(actor, params \\ %{}, opts \\ [])` - Returns `{:ok, true/false}` or `{:error, reason}`
117 |
118 |Example usage:
119 |```elixir
120 |# Check if user can create a post
121 |if MyApp.Blog.can_create_post?(current_user) do
122 |  # Show create button
123 |end
124 |
125 |# Check if user can update a specific post
126 |if MyApp.Blog.can_update_post?(current_user, post) do
127 |  # Show edit button
128 |end
129 |
130 |# Check if user can destroy a specific comment
131 |if MyApp.Blog.can_destroy_comment?(current_user, comment) do
132 |  # Show delete button
133 |end
134 |```
135 |
136 |These functions are particularly useful for conditional rendering of UI elements based on user permissions.
137 |
138 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/code_structure.md

1 |# Code Structure & Organization
2 |
3 |- Organize code around domains and resources
4 |- Each resource should be focused and well-named
5 |- Create domain-specific actions rather than generic CRUD operations
6 |- Put business logic inside actions rather than in external modules
7 |- Use resources to model your domain entities
8 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/data_layers.md

1  |# Data Layers
2  |
3  |Data layers determine how resources are stored and retrieved. Examples of data layers:
4  |
5  |- **Postgres**: For storing resources in PostgreSQL (via `AshPostgres`)
6  |- **ETS**: For in-memory storage (`Ash.DataLayer.Ets`)
7  |- **Mnesia**: For distributed storage (`Ash.DataLayer.Mnesia`)
8  |- **Embedded**: For resources embedded in other resources (`data_layer: :embedded`) (typically JSON under the hood)
9  |- **Ash.DataLayer.Simple**: For resources that aren't persisted at all. Leave off the data layer, as this is the default.
10 |
11 |Specify a data layer when defining a resource:
12 |
13 |```elixir
14 |defmodule MyApp.Post do
15 |  use Ash.Resource,
16 |    domain: MyApp.Blog,
17 |    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer
18 |
19 |  postgres do
20 |    table "posts"
21 |    repo MyApp.Repo
22 |  end
23 |
24 |  # ... attributes, relationships, etc.
25 |end
26 |```
27 |
28 |For embedded resources:
29 |
30 |```elixir
31 |defmodule MyApp.Address do
32 |  use Ash.Resource,
33 |    data_layer: :embedded
34 |
35 |  attributes do
36 |    attribute :street, :string
37 |    attribute :city, :string
38 |    attribute :state, :string
39 |    attribute :zip, :string
40 |  end
41 |end
42 |```
43 |
44 |Each data layer has its own configuration options and capabilities. Refer to the rules & documentation of the specific data layer package for more details.
45 |
46 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/exist_expressions.md

1  |# Exists Expressions
2  |
3  |Use `exists/2` to check for the existence of records, either through relationships or unrelated resources:
4  |
5  |### Related Exists
6  |
7  |```elixir
8  |# Check if user has any admin roles
9  |Ash.Query.filter(User, exists(roles, name == "admin"))
10 |
11 |# Check if post has comments with high scores
12 |Ash.Query.filter(Post, exists(comments, score > 50))
13 |```
14 |
15 |### Unrelated Exists
16 |
17 |```elixir
18 |# Check if any profile exists with the same name
19 |Ash.Query.filter(User, exists(Profile, name == parent(name)))
20 |
21 |# Check if user has any reports
22 |Ash.Query.filter(User, exists(Report, author_name == parent(name)))
23 |
24 |# Complex existence checks
25 |Ash.Query.filter(User, 
26 |  active == true and 
27 |  exists(Profile, active == true and name == parent(name))
28 |)
29 |```
30 |
31 |Unrelated exists expressions automatically apply authorization using the target resource's primary read action. Use `parent/1` to reference fields from the source resource.
32 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/generating_code.md

1 |# Generating Code
2 |
3 |Use `mix ash.gen.*` tasks as a basis for code generation when possible. Check the task docs with `mix help <task>`.
4 |Be sure to use `--yes` to bypass confirmation prompts. Use `--yes --dry-run` to preview the changes.
5 |
6 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/migrations.md

1 |# Migrations and Schema Changes
2 |
3 |After creating or modifying Ash code, run `mix ash.codegen <short_name_describing_changes>` to ensure any required additional changes are made (like migrations are generated). The name of the migration should be lower_snake_case. In a longer running dev session it's usually better to use `mix ash.codegen --dev` as you go and at the end run the final codegen with a sensible name describing all the changes made in the session.
4 |
5 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/query_filter.md

1  |# Ash.Query.filter is a macro
2  |
3  |**Important**: You must `require Ash.Query` if you want to use `Ash.Query.filter/2`, as it is a macro.
4  |
5  |If you see errors like the following:
6  |
7  |```
8  |Ash.Query.filter(MyResource, id == ^id)
9  |error: misplaced operator ^id
10 |
11 |The pin operator ^ is supported only inside matches or inside custom macros...
12 |```
13 |
14 |```
15 |iex(3)> Ash.Query.filter(MyResource, something == true)
16 |error: undefined variable "something"
17 |└─ iex:3
18 |```
19 |
20 |You are very likely missing a `require Ash.Query`
21 |
22 |## Common Query Operations
23 |
24 |- **Filter**: `Ash.Query.filter(query, field == value)`
25 |- **Sort**: `Ash.Query.sort(query, field: :asc)`
26 |- **Load relationships**: `Ash.Query.load(query, [:author, :comments])`
27 |- **Limit**: `Ash.Query.limit(query, 10)`
28 |- **Offset**: `Ash.Query.offset(query, 20)`
29 |
30 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/querying_data.md

1 |# Querying Data
2 |
3 |Use `Ash.Query` to build queries for reading data from your resources. The query module provides a declarative way to filter, sort, and load data.
4 |
5 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/relationships.md

1   |# Relationships
2   |
3   |Relationships describe connections between resources and are a core component of Ash. Define relationships in the `relationships` block of a resource.
4   |
5   |## Best Practices for Relationships
6   |
7   |- Be descriptive with relationship names (e.g., use `:authored_posts` instead of just `:posts`)
8   |- Configure foreign key constraints in your data layer if they have them (see `references` in AshPostgres)
9   |- Always choose the appropriate relationship type based on your domain model
10  |
11  |### Relationship Types
12  |
13  |- For Polymorphic relationships, you can model them using `Ash.Type.Union`; see the “Polymorphic Relationships” guide for more information.
14  |
15  |```elixir
16  |relationships do
17  |  # belongs_to - adds foreign key to source resource
18  |  belongs_to :owner, MyApp.User do
19  |    allow_nil? false
20  |    attribute_type :integer  # defaults to :uuid
21  |  end
22  |
23  |  # has_one - foreign key on destination resource
24  |  has_one :profile, MyApp.Profile
25  |
26  |  # has_many - foreign key on destination resource, returns list
27  |  has_many :posts, MyApp.Post do
28  |    filter expr(published == true)
29  |    sort published_at: :desc
30  |  end
31  |
32  |  # many_to_many - requires join resource
33  |  many_to_many :tags, MyApp.Tag do
34  |    through MyApp.PostTag
35  |    source_attribute_on_join_resource :post_id
36  |    destination_attribute_on_join_resource :tag_id
37  |  end
38  |end
39  |```
40  |
41  |The join resource must be defined separately:
42  |
43  |```elixir
44  |defmodule MyApp.PostTag do
45  |  use Ash.Resource,
46  |    data_layer: AshPostgres.DataLayer
47  |
48  |  attributes do
49  |    uuid_primary_key :id
50  |    # Add additional attributes if you need metadata on the relationship
51  |    attribute :added_at, :utc_datetime_usec do
52  |      default &DateTime.utc_now/0
53  |    end
54  |  end
55  |
56  |  relationships do
57  |    belongs_to :post, MyApp.Post, primary_key?: true, allow_nil?: false
58  |    belongs_to :tag, MyApp.Tag, primary_key?: true, allow_nil?: false
59  |  end
60  |
61  |  actions do
62  |    defaults [:read, :destroy, create: :*, update: :*]
63  |  end
64  |end
65  |```
66  |
67  |## Loading Relationships
68  |
69  |```elixir
70  |# Using code interface options (preferred)
71  |post = MyDomain.get_post!(id, load: [:author, comments: [:author]])
72  |
73  |# Complex loading with filters
74  |posts = MyDomain.list_posts!(
75  |  query: [load: [comments: [filter: [is_approved: true], limit: 5]]]
76  |)
77  |
78  |# Manual query building (for complex cases)
79  |MyApp.Post
80  ||> Ash.Query.load(comments: MyApp.Comment |> Ash.Query.filter(is_approved == true))
81  ||> Ash.read!()
82  |
83  |# Loading on existing records
84  |Ash.load!(post, :author)
85  |```
86  |
87  |Prefer to use the `strict?` option when loading to only load necessary fields on related data.
88  |
89  |```elixir
90  |MyApp.Post
91  ||> Ash.Query.load([comments: [:title]], strict?: true)
92  |```
93  |
94  |## Managing Relationships
95  |
96  |There are two primary ways to manage relationships in Ash:
97  |
98  |### 1. Using `change manage_relationship/2-3` in Actions
99  |Use this when input comes from action arguments:
100 |
101 |```elixir
102 |actions do
103 |  update :update do
104 |    # Define argument for the related data
105 |    argument :comments, {:array, :map} do
106 |      allow_nil? false
107 |    end
108 |
109 |    argument :new_tags, {:array, :map}
110 |
111 |    # Link argument to relationship management
112 |    change manage_relationship(:comments, type: :append)
113 |
114 |    # For different argument and relationship names
115 |    change manage_relationship(:new_tags, :tags, type: :append)
116 |  end
117 |end
118 |```
119 |
120 |### 2. Using `Ash.Changeset.manage_relationship/3-4` in Custom Changes
121 |Use this when building values programmatically:
122 |
123 |```elixir
124 |defmodule MyApp.Changes.AssignTeamMembers do
125 |  use Ash.Resource.Change
126 |
127 |  def change(changeset, _opts, context) do
128 |    members = determine_team_members(changeset, context.actor)
129 |
130 |    Ash.Changeset.manage_relationship(
131 |      changeset,
132 |      :members,
133 |      members,
134 |      type: :append_and_remove
135 |    )
136 |  end
137 |end
138 |```
139 |
140 |### Quick Reference - Management Types
141 |- `:append` - Add new related records, ignore existing
142 |- `:append_and_remove` - Add new related records, remove missing
143 |- `:remove` - Remove specified related records
144 |- `:direct_control` - Full CRUD control (create/update/destroy)
145 |- `:create` - Only create new records
146 |
147 |### Quick Reference - Common Options
148 |- `on_lookup: :relate` - Look up and relate existing records
149 |- `on_no_match: :create` - Create if no match found
150 |- `on_match: :update` - Update existing matches
151 |- `on_missing: :destroy` - Delete records not in input
152 |- `value_is_key: :name` - Use field as key for simple values
153 |
154 |For comprehensive documentation, see the [Managing Relationships](https://hexdocs.pm/ash/relationships.html#managing-relationships) section.
155 |
156 |### Examples
157 |
158 |Creating a post with tags:
159 |```elixir
160 |MyDomain.create_post!(%{
161 |  title: "New Post",
162 |  body: "Content here...",
163 |  tags: [%{name: "elixir"}, %{name: "ash"}]  # Creates new tags
164 |})
165 |
166 |# Updating a post to replace its tags
167 |MyDomain.update_post!(post, %{
168 |  tags: [tag1.id, tag2.id]  # Replaces tags with existing ones by ID
169 |})
170 |```
171 |
172 |


Create: .claude/skills/bolty/references/testing.md

1  |# Testing
2  |
3  |When testing resources:
4  |- Test your domain actions through the code interface
5  |- Use test utilities in `Ash.Test`
6  |- Test authorization policies work as expected using `Ash.can?`
7  |- Use `authorize?: false` in tests where authorization is not the focus
8  |- Write generators using `Ash.Generator`
9  |- Prefer to use raising versions of functions whenever possible, as opposed to pattern matching
10 |
11 |## Preventing Deadlocks in Concurrent Tests
12 |
13 |When running tests concurrently, using fixed values for identity attributes can cause deadlock errors. Multiple tests attempting to create records with the same unique values will conflict.
14 |
15 |### Use Globally Unique Values
16 |
17 |Always use globally unique values for identity attributes in tests:
18 |
19 |```elixir
20 |# BAD - Can cause deadlocks in concurrent tests
21 |%{email: "test@example.com", username: "testuser"}
22 |
23 |# GOOD - Use globally unique values
24 |%{
25 |  email: "test-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}@example.com",
26 |  username: "user_#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}",
27 |  slug: "post-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
28 |}
29 |```
30 |
31 |### Creating Reusable Test Generators
32 |
33 |For better organization, create a generator module:
34 |
35 |```elixir
36 |defmodule MyApp.TestGenerators do
37 |  use Ash.Generator
38 |
39 |  def user(opts \\ []) do
40 |    changeset_generator(
41 |      User,
42 |      :create,
43 |      defaults: [
44 |        email: "user-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}@example.com",
45 |        username: "user_#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
46 |      ],
47 |      overrides: opts
48 |    )
49 |  end
50 |end
51 |
52 |# In your tests
53 |test "concurrent user creation" do
54 |  users = MyApp.TestGenerators.generate_many(user(), 10)
55 |  # Each user has unique identity attributes
56 |end
57 |```
58 |
59 |This applies to ANY field used in identity constraints, not just primary keys. Using globally unique values prevents frustrating intermittent test failures in CI environments.
60 |

